\begin_layout Subsection
Phase transitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Landau phenomenological approach, or Landau–Devonshire theory, we
 can write the free energy 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of a ferroelectric in the mean-field approach as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=F_{0}+\frac{\alpha}{2}P+\frac{\beta}{4}P^{2}+\frac{\gamma}{6}P^{6}\cdots-EP\label{eq:Landau-Free-Energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, etc are the Landau parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

is the free energy density of the disordered (high temperature) phase near
 the transition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 the external field.
 In the paraelectric phase the Hamiltonian must be invariant under a transformat
ion from 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-P$
\end_inset

, forcing equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Landau-Free-Energy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to only contain even powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 The Landau parameters are pressure and temperature dependent, though usually
 only the temperature dependence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is considered.
 The first parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is generally taken as linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 near the transition temperature, taking on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha_{0}\left(T-T_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the Curie–Weiss transition temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}\leq T_{C}$
\end_inset

).
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Landau-Free-Energy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be modified to fit thin film ferroelectrics by including the boundary
 conditions
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wong2007asimplified"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, but we will keep to the simpler, bulk description.
 Minimizing the free energy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial F}{\partial P}=\alpha P+\beta P^{3}+\gamma P^{5}-E=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then setting 
\begin_inset Formula $E=0$
\end_inset

 we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{2}=\begin{cases}
0 & Paraelectric\\
\frac{-\beta\pm\sqrt{\beta^{2}-4\alpha\gamma}}{2\gamma} & Ferroelectric
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We can then look at three separate cases for equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Landau-Free-Energy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

