\begin_layout Subsection
Ferroelectric field-effect transistors (FeFETs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ferroelectric field-effect transistors (FeFETs), 1T cell, seek to keep a
 persistent on/off binary state.
 A ferroelectric dielectric replaces the typical oxide gate dielectric of
 a (MOS)FET, using the gate to switch the polarization of the crystal, figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Typical-FeFET-device"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The polarization of the material should maintain an electric field along
 the junction with the semiconductor, providing the normal enhancement or
 depletion of the channel.
 As a normal FET, a conducting channel is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and conversely, current reduced below a threshold can be considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

off.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 While as the polarization persists the channel state should remain on or
 off, sustaining it without power.
 This has the potential to replace or augment DRAM in computers and low
 power devices, reducing active energy consumption or possibly allowing
 electronics to turn on without a lengthy start.
 FeFETs also offer the possibility of faster switching than traditional
 capacitor-based RAM
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "park2020ferroelectricgate"
literal "true"

\end_inset

