 When the voltage across the gate is reduced to 0 V the polarization continues
 to provide an electric field at the surface and maintaining the conduction
 channel and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state, figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FeFET-Hold-ON"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Further decreasing the gate voltage to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state subsequently polarizes the dielectric in the opposite direction,
 figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FeFET-channel-Write-OFF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The electric field of the gate depletes the channel of carriers, giving
 the desired diminutive drain current.
 When the gate voltage is again returned to 0 V the polarization preserves
 the depletion field within the channel until the gate is switched to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 again, figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FeFET-channel-Hold-OFF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "georgiou2018ferroelectricity2,park2020ferroelectricgate"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For both the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 states the multiple factors causes the polarization to decay once the electric
 field is reduced below the threshold of the coercive field, eventually
 leading to the depolarization of the device.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the piratical challenges of FeFETs is increasing the longevity of
 the polarization state.
 Often thermal energy may cause the polarization to relax over time as the
 dipoles reorient so materials must be chosen to minimize this effect.
 Likely the largest cause of long term polarization degradation is leakage
 current through the gate
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "park2020ferroelectricgate"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A common modification of FeFETs is to include a dielectric layer between
 the ferroelectric and semiconductor to improve the interface between the
 two (MFIS-FET) and reduce leak currents higher energy electrons from damaging
 the ferroelectric.
 Another is to add a floating metal and dielectric layer forming a metal-ferroel
ectric and channel (MFMIS-FET) to redistribute the electric field evenly
 over the channel and reduce the effect of domain formation within the ferroelec
tric.
 Improving film quality to reduce trapped charges, increasing the metal-ferroele
ctric Schottky barrier, and using a high-k dielectric can be used to further
 reduce leak currents in a FeFET 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "park2020ferroelectricgate"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Another common challenge with producing a commercial FeFET RAM is fatigue
 in the ferroelectric layer as conventional RAM is expected to be able to
 switch 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{12}$
\end_inset

 in its lifetime
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "park2020ferroelectricgate"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ferroelectric tunnel junctions (FTJs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ferroelectric tunnel junctions (FTJs) are an alternative to FeFETs being
 explored for data storage
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bain2017ferroelectrics"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 They consist of a thin ferroelectric in between two metal electrodes, where
 the ferroelectric polarization is along the axis of the metal-ferroelectric-met
al structure, figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FTJ-Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kohlstedt2005theoretical,shen2019twodimensional"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The polarization direction will produce a net positive and negative charge
 distribution in the ferroelectric along the respective electrode junction,
 figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FTJ-Charge-distribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The electrons in the metal will adjust to screen out the charge at the
 junction, all together producing a varying potential across the junction.
 When a voltage is placed across the FTJ some electrons will tunnel though
 the barrier forming a measurable current.
 The voltage produces an electric field across the ferroelectric, and if
 large enough will cause the polarization to switch.
 The switched polarization will alter the potential across the two junctions
 and the tunneling current.
 By measuring the current at a particular voltage it is possible to determine
 which direction the polarization is orientated giving rise to a binary
 state that can be used to store information.
 If the voltage is kept below the coercive field the FTJ will act similar
 to a non-ferroelectric junction allowing the current state to be read out
 without being overwritten.
 Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FTJ-Current-vs-voltage-sym"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FTJ-Current-vs-voltage-asym"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 show two possible resistive switching behaviors, the first with symmetric
 electrode-ferroelectric interfaces, the second with asymmetric interfaces.
\end_layout

