\begin_layout Subsection
Polar metals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Polar metals, metals that contain dipoles, were first proposed in 1965
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "anderson1965symmetry"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 to explain the structural transition in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{3}Si$
\end_inset

 but only recently seen experimental verification in 
\begin_inset Formula $LiOsO_{3}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shi2013aferroelectriclike"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Polar metals must show a continuous phase transition from non-polar to
 polar at their Curie temperature
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "benedek2016textquoteleftferroelectrictextquoteright"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 breaking inversion symmetry.
 As metals have an abundance of free charge carriers, the electric fields
 within the material are screened, suggesting that metallicity is the antithesis
 to both prerequisites in the traditional definition of ferroelectricity.
 The carrier screening suppresses long-range coulomb interactions necessary
 for dipole formation and the fields to orient the dipoles.
 
\begin_inset Formula $LiOsO_{3}$
\end_inset

was shown to shift from 
\begin_inset Formula $R\bar{3}c$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $R3c$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=140\,K$
\end_inset

 by the shifting of the Li ion
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shi2013aferroelectriclike"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, forming a similar structure to several insulating ferroelectrics, and
 accompanied by several changes in the optical and electronic properties
 attributed to the dipole formation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "padmanabhan2018linearand,shi2013aferroelectriclike,jin2019ramaninterrogation,laurita2019evidence"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Similar dipole formation has been seen in 
\begin_inset Formula $Ca_{3}Ru_{2}O_{7}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lei2018observation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $BaTiO_{3}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "takahashi2017polarmetal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $LaAuGe$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $LaPtSb$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "du2019highelectrical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and other materials.
 Ferroelectricity was reported in 2-3 layer 
\begin_inset Formula $WTe_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fei2018ferroelectric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, a 2D Van der Waals chalcogenide metal.
 The 2D material was stacked between two insulating layers of hexagonal
 Boron Nitrite (
\begin_inset Formula $hBN$
\end_inset

) in a double-gated FeFET.
 The gating response showed a clear transition behavior in 
\begin_inset Formula $WTe_{2}$
\end_inset

 conductivity while the thin graphene layers used to gate the material showed
 a hysteresis in their conductivity, both are attributed to the polarized
 electric field from the 
\begin_inset Formula $WTe_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Later measurements demonstrated the existence of ferroelectric domains
 with bulk crystals and thin films
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sharma2019aroomtemperature"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The free carriers in a polar metal may move to the edges of the material,
 to the excess electrical charge normally found on the surface of insulating
 ferroelectrics, instead producing a neutral charge distribution.
 This freedom can remove the depolarization field found in a typical ferroelectr
ic
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lei2018observation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 possibly extending the polarized state of the crystal.
 The charge screening also lowers the system energy from domain walls of
 different dipole orientations in close proximity, allowing for opposing
 polarization domains to form 
\begin_inset Formula $1nm$
\end_inset

 apart with only 10s of 
\begin_inset Formula $meV$
\end_inset

 potential difference
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "stone2019atomicand"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Potential polar metal applications include reducing the size of ferroelectric
 capacitors
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "puggioni2018polarmetals"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, FeFETs
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fei2018ferroelectric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, tunnel barriers
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fang2020designof"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and nonreciprocal charge transport
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tokura2018nonreciprocal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

